aVWhen I think back to my childhood,
p383
aVa good part of which I spent, after being born here in Chicago,
p384
aVI spent in Europe.
p385
aVIf you had been in the ruins of, say, London in 1945, or Berlin,
p386
aVand you had said,
p387
aV"Sixty years from now,
p388
aVthis is going to be the most peaceful, prosperous part of the planet,"
p389
aVpeople would have thought you were certifiably insane.
p390
aVBut they did it, thanks to a common identity, Europe,
p391
aVand a common economy.
p392
aVSo my question is, if it can be done in Europe,
p393
aVwhy not in the Middle East?
p394
aVWhy not, thanks to a common identity, which is the story of Abraham,
p395
aVand thanks to a common economy that would be based, in good part, on tourism?
